hook.real_world_problem:
Your product API is feature-complete. How do you know it works?

```
Manual testing:
- Start the server
- Open Postman
- POST a product... check 201
- GET it back... check 200
- DELETE it... check 204
- GET again... check 404
- Test invalid data... check 400
- Repeat for every scenario...
→ 15 minutes per change. Teams skip it. Bugs ship.
```

**Spring Boot testing — automated in seconds:**

```java
// Controller test — no database, no server startup:
@WebMvcTest(ProductController.class)
class ProductControllerTest {
    @Autowired MockMvc mvc;
    @MockBean ProductService service;

    @Test
    void createProduct_valid_returns201() throws Exception {
        when(service.create(any())).thenReturn(savedProduct);
        mvc.perform(post("/api/products")
                .contentType(APPLICATION_JSON)
                .content("{\"name\":\"Mouse\",\"price\":799}"))
            .andExpect(status().isCreated())
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$.id").exists())
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$.name").value("Mouse"));
    }

    @Test
    void createProduct_blankName_returns400() throws Exception {
        mvc.perform(post("/api/products")
                .contentType(APPLICATION_JSON)
                .content("{\"name\":\"\",\"price\":799}"))
            .andExpect(status().isBadRequest())
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$.name").value("Name is required"));
    }
}
// Runs in 500ms. Tests everything. No manual work.
```

Three test slices, three purposes:
- **@WebMvcTest**: HTTP layer — controllers, validation, error handling. No database.
- **@DataJpaTest**: Data layer — repositories, queries. No HTTP.
- **@SpringBootTest**: Full stack — everything together.

concept_explanation.web_mvc_test:
**@WebMvcTest — testing the HTTP layer in isolation:**

```java
import org.springframework.boot.test.autoconfigure.web.servlet.WebMvcTest;
import org.springframework.boot.test.mock.mockito.MockBean;
import org.springframework.test.web.servlet.MockMvc;
import static org.springframework.test.web.servlet.request.MockMvcRequestBuilders.*;
import static org.springframework.test.web.servlet.result.MockMvcResultMatchers.*;
import static org.springframework.http.MediaType.*;

@WebMvcTest(ProductController.class)  // loads ONLY this controller + security config
class ProductControllerTest {

    @Autowired MockMvc mvc;              // the HTTP test client
    @Autowired ObjectMapper mapper;      // for JSON serialization
    @MockBean ProductService service;    // mock all dependencies!

    @Test
    void getAll_returns200WithList() throws Exception {
        // Arrange:
        when(service.findAll()).thenReturn(List.of(
            new Product("P001", "Mouse", 799),
            new Product("P002", "Keyboard", 1999)));

        // Act + Assert:
        mvc.perform(get("/api/products"))
            .andExpect(status().isOk())
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$").isArray())
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$.length()").value(2))
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$[0].name").value("Mouse"))
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$[1].price").value(1999));
    }
}
```

**What @WebMvcTest loads:**
- The specified controller class
- @ControllerAdvice / @RestControllerAdvice beans
- Jackson (JSON serialization)
- MockMvc

**What @WebMvcTest does NOT load:**
- @Service beans (use @MockBean)
- @Repository beans
- The database
- The full application context

concept_explanation.mock_mvc:
**MockMvc — the HTTP test DSL:**

```java
// GET request:
mvc.perform(get("/api/products/{id}", "P001")
        .header("Authorization", "Bearer test-token"))
    .andExpect(status().isOk())
    .andExpect(content().contentType(APPLICATION_JSON))
    .andExpect(jsonPath("$.id").value("P001"))
    .andExpect(jsonPath("$.name").value("Mouse"));

// POST with JSON body:
Product request = new Product(null, "Mouse", 799);
mvc.perform(post("/api/products")
        .contentType(APPLICATION_JSON)
        .content(mapper.writeValueAsString(request)))
    .andExpect(status().isCreated())
    .andExpect(header().exists("Location"))
    .andExpect(jsonPath("$.id").exists());

// DELETE:
mvc.perform(delete("/api/products/{id}", "P001"))
    .andExpect(status().isNoContent());

// Query parameters:
mvc.perform(get("/api/products/search")
        .param("name", "mouse")
        .param("maxPrice", "1000"))
    .andExpect(status().isOk())
    .andExpect(jsonPath("$").isArray());

// Common status matchers:
// isOk() = 200, isCreated() = 201, isNoContent() = 204
// isBadRequest() = 400, isNotFound() = 404, isConflict() = 409

// jsonPath() expressions:
// '$' = root, '$.field' = field, '$[0]' = first element
// '$.items[*].name' = all name fields in items array
```

concept_explanation.data_jpa_test_advanced:
**@DataJpaTest — repository slice:**

```java
@DataJpaTest  // H2 + JPA only; no controllers, no services
@Import(ProductService.class)  // import services you need
class ProductServiceRepositoryTest {

    @Autowired ProductRepository repo;
    @Autowired ProductService service;  // imported above

    @BeforeEach
    void seed() {
        repo.save(new Product("Mouse",    799,  "Electronics"));
        repo.save(new Product("Keyboard", 1999, "Electronics"));
        repo.save(new Product("Chair",    5000, "Furniture"));
    }

    @Test
    void findByCategory_electronics_returns2() {
        List<Product> result = repo.findByCategory("Electronics");
        assertEquals(2, result.size());
    }

    @Test
    void create_duplicate_throws() {
        // service imported — test the full service logic
        assertThrows(DuplicateResourceException.class,
            () -> service.create(new ProductRequest("Mouse", 999.0, "Electronics", 5)));
    }

    // Each @Test runs in a transaction that ROLLS BACK after
    // seed() re-runs before each test — clean state guaranteed
}
```

**@Import(ServiceClass.class)**: import a service bean into the DataJpaTest slice. Without this, the service is not in the context.

concept_explanation.spring_boot_test_full:
**@SpringBootTest — full integration test:**

```java
// Full stack: HTTP → Controller → Service → Repository → H2
@SpringBootTest(webEnvironment = SpringBootTest.WebEnvironment.RANDOM_PORT)
class ProductApiIntegrationTest {

    @Autowired TestRestTemplate rest;  // HTTP client for tests
    @Autowired ProductRepository repo;  // optional: check DB state

    @Test
    void fullCrudLifecycle() {
        // CREATE:
        var createResp = rest.postForEntity(
            "/api/products",
            new ProductRequest("Mouse", 799.0, "Electronics", 50),
            Product.class);
        assertEquals(HttpStatus.CREATED, createResp.getStatusCode());
        String id = createResp.getBody().getId();

        // READ:
        var getResp = rest.getForEntity("/api/products/" + id, Product.class);
        assertEquals(HttpStatus.OK, getResp.getStatusCode());
        assertEquals("Mouse", getResp.getBody().getName());

        // DELETE:
        rest.delete("/api/products/" + id);

        // VERIFY 404:
        var notFound = rest.getForEntity("/api/products/" + id, String.class);
        assertEquals(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND, notFound.getStatusCode());
    }
}
```

**WebEnvironment options:**
- `RANDOM_PORT`: starts real Tomcat on a random port — true end-to-end
- `MOCK` (default): mock servlet environment — like @WebMvcTest but full context
- `NONE`: no web environment — for testing service beans only

